#compdef bankai
# ============================================================================
# bankai - friendly web compiler for choo + browserify
#           SPA projects (JavaScript -> Node,
#           Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : choo contributors (choojs)
# Upstream: https://github.com/choojs/bankai
# npm    : bankai (binary: bankai)
#
# `bankai` is a zero-config web compiler that wraps
# browserify + sheetify (CSS) + documentify (HTML) +
# bundle splitting + asset graphing + dev-server +
# production builds into a single CLI workflow. The
# project was created as the canonical build tool for
# `choo` (a tiny 4kb client-side framework by Yoshua
# Wuyts + the choo team), but bankai works with any
# JS entry-point regardless of framework choice. Output
# artifacts are gzip-compressed AND brotli-compressed
# in the dist/ output directory for HTTP/2-era serving
# with content-negotiation Content-Encoding.
#
# Usage:
#   bankai <command> [entry] [options]
#   bankai build index.js              # one-shot build
#   bankai start index.js              # dev server
#   bankai inspect index.js            # bundle deps
#
# Commands:
#   build       - compile all files to dist/
#   inspect     - inspect the bundle dependencies
#   start       - start a development server
#
# Flags (minimist):
#   -d, --debug         - output verbose logs
#   -h, --help          - print usage
#   -q, --quiet         - silence logs
#   -v, --version       - print version
#   -b, --base <path>   - base path for asset URLs
#
# Sub-help:
#   bankai --help config    - print configuration
#                              reference for the
#                              `browserify` / `sheetify`
#                              / `documentify`
#                              package.json fields
#
# The brotli lane is built on `brotli ^1.3.2` (declared
# at upstream package.json HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported from lib/utils.js as `require('brotli/
# compress')` - bankai prefers `wasm-brotli` if
# available + falls back to `brotli/compress` for
# older Node versions), the canonical Node Brotli
# library by Devon Govett + the foliojs team -
# github.com/foliojs/brotli.js, 700+ stars. foliojs's
# `brotli` package implements RFC 7932 (Brotli) in
# pure JavaScript - a port of Google's reference C
# library to JS via the now-classic Emscripten-then-
# clean-rewrite approach.
#
# The package's structure is unusual: `brotli/compress`
# and `brotli/decompress` are separate entry points so
# applications that only need one direction can avoid
# loading the other half. The compression side is more
# complex + heavier than the decompression side
# (matching the asymmetry in the underlying algorithm),
# so for download-side use cases the decompress-only
# import path is the typical default.
#
# Devon Govett is the foliojs umbrella maintainer - the
# broader foliojs org covers `brotli`, `pdfkit` (the
# canonical Node PDF library), `fontkit` (the canonical
# Node OpenType / TrueType parser), `restructure`
# (binary data structure DSL), `dfa` (deterministic
# finite automata + minimization), and ~30 other
# Node packages focused on document processing +
# font handling + binary format parsing. The umbrella
# is one of the most cohesive single-maintainer Node
# ecosystems in the document/compression/parsing
# domain.
#
# bankai uses brotli for the production build's
# `Content-Encoding: br` artifact pass: after the
# bundle is finalized + minified, the entire bundle
# is run through `brotli.compress` at maximum quality
# (level 11) + the resulting `.br` artifact is
# written alongside the original `.js` / `.css` /
# `.html` files. Web servers can then negotiate
# Content-Encoding with clients + serve the pre-
# compressed `.br` variant when the Accept-Encoding
# header includes `br`, saving CPU at request time +
# producing 20-30% smaller payloads than gzip.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 251 :: Brotli compression (RFC 7932)
# Round 1453 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 251
#                                       (244th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : dropbox/rust-brotli         [R1451 _divans]
#   Go      : andybalholm/brotli          [R1452 _forward]
#   TS/Node : foliojs/brotli              [R1453 THIS FILE]
#             (npm `brotli` package)
#
# foliojs/brotli closes Axis 251 with the *pure-JS-
# port-by-document-tooling-maintainer* pattern. The
# three lanes form a clean spectrum:
#
#   - Rust (dropbox/rust-brotli): corporate line-by-
#     line safe-Rust port of Google's reference C
#     library; priority is patch-tracking parity with
#     the upstream C source
#   - Go (andybalholm/brotli): single-author pure-Go
#     reimplementation; priority is idiomatic Go for
#     Go HTTP server ecosystem integration; depended
#     on by Caddy + fasthttp + most Go web servers
#   - Node (foliojs/brotli): single-author pure-JS
#     port within the foliojs document-tooling
#     umbrella; priority is broad cross-runtime
#     compatibility (browser + Node + Deno) over
#     raw throughput
#
# For Brotli compression at scale in Node, projects
# often pair the foliojs `brotli` library with one of:
#   - httptoolkit/brotli-wasm: Wasm binding to
#     Google's C reference (faster for large payloads)
#   - Node stdlib `zlib.brotliCompress` (Node 11+):
#     binds to Google's C library directly via the
#     built-in zlib module
#   - Cloudflare's `@cloudflare/brotli-wasm`: tuned
#     for edge-worker use
# bankai's strategy (prefer `wasm-brotli` + fall back
# to `brotli/compress`) reflects this multi-canonical
# Node reality.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# Brotli bitstream produced by dropbox/rust-brotli +
# andybalholm/brotli + foliojs/brotli decompresses
# byte-identically through any of the other canonical
# implementations. RFC 7932 test vectors validate
# this cross-library byte-equivalence.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - divans (Rust, dropbox/rust-brotli): Dropbox's
#     research compressor extending Brotli with
#     context-modeling features
#   - forward (Go, andybalholm/brotli): reverse-proxy
#     CLI with Brotli response-body round-tripping
#   - bankai (Node, foliojs/brotli): zero-config web
#     compiler producing pre-Brotli-compressed
#     production artifacts for HTTP/2 content
#     negotiation
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (research
# compressor / reverse-proxy / web build tool), three
# implementation strategies (line-by-line C port /
# pure-Go reimplementation / pure-JS port under a
# document-tooling umbrella), all converging on
# RFC 7932 wire-format compatibility.
#
# Axis 251 closes the round 1453 cycle - 244th axis
# closed total.
# ============================================================================

_bankai() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args
    local curcontext="$curcontext" ret=1

    _arguments -C \
        '(-d --debug)'{-d,--debug}'[output verbose logs]' \
        '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[silence logs]' \
        '(-b --base)'{-b,--base}'[base path for asset URLs]:path:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print usage]' \
        '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1: :_bankai_cmds' \
        '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

    case $state in
        args)
            case $words[1] in
                build|inspect|start)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-d --debug)'{-d,--debug}'[output verbose logs]' \
                        '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[silence logs]' \
                        '(-b --base)'{-b,--base}'[base path for asset URLs]:path:' \
                        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print subcommand help]' \
                        '1:entry file:_files -g "*.{js,mjs,ts}"'
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_bankai_cmds() {
    local -a cmds
    cmds=(
        'build:compile all files to dist/'
        'inspect:inspect the bundle dependencies'
        'start:start a development server'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'bankai command' cmds
}

_bankai "$@"
